# Operations Decisions

The long-form architecture source of truth is `docs/architecture/operations-system-v1.md`.

Current decisions:

- Old project is business reference only.
- SQL Server is the v1.0.0 database.
- MediatR is the initial mediator.
- Public API routes start with `/api/v1`.
- Redis is not included by default in v1.0.0.
- Quartz.NET is the v1.0.0 background job scheduler.
- List endpoints use explicit query parameters.
- Permission names use `module.resource.action`.
- Users have exactly one role in v1.0.0.
- Transactional integration events use outbox/inbox processing.
- Central Package Management is required.
- v1.0.0 is single-tenant; tenancy is deferred but not designed out.
- The product is bilingual (Arabic and English) with full RTL support.
- The old Blazor solution is copied under `legacy/` as read-only business reference.
- Timestamps are stored and exchanged in UTC; localization happens at the edges.
- Editable records use optimistic concurrency (rowversion + ETag/`If-Match`, 409 on conflict).
- Web stores the access token in memory with an httpOnly refresh-token cookie.
- No secrets in source; configuration is environment-driven.
- Rewrite progress is tracked in `docs/architecture/migration-inventory.md`.
- Domain/application use the Result/Error pattern; one central mapper converts errors to ProblemDetails.
- Cross-module references use immutable point-in-time snapshots, not live foreign keys into other modules.
- Business numbers (contract/work-order) use an explicit, scoped, concurrency-safe sequence (the documented exception to optimistic concurrency).
- Aggregate updates may rebuild child graphs but must preserve derived/consumed state (balances, history) by stable id.
- Seed data uses fixed stable GUIDs; a fixed `SystemUserId` is the actor for automated/background actions.
- Web real-time is delivered via SignalR; notification delivery sits behind a composite pusher abstraction so mobile push (FCM) can be added later.
- Attachments are stored in object/file storage (local filesystem in v1.0.0, cloud-ready); the database stores only metadata.
- Instants standardize on `DateTimeOffset`.
- Authorization has two axes: permission checks and station-based data scoping (row-level), both enforced server-side.
- The auth foundation supports cookie (web) and Bearer (future mobile) schemes, selected per endpoint.
- The mobile client (BFF, offline sync, FCM push, mobile JWT policy) is deferred for v1.0.0 but not designed out.
- Identity is implemented with custom DDD aggregates (User/Role/UserSession), not the ASP.NET Core Identity framework.
- Passwords are hashed with the ASP.NET Core `PasswordHasher` (PBKDF2); no extra hashing dependency.
- Tests use xUnit + Shouldly/FluentAssertions + NSubstitute, with Testcontainers for integration tests.
- DTO mapping is manual and explicit; no mapping library.
- The web client is a Blazor Web App (.NET, Interactive Auto render mode) using Radzen.Blazor (Material3 theme) as the only UI component library; no React/Vite/Tailwind/Orval. (Changed 2026-06-19; was React/Vite/Tailwind/shadcn/Orval.)
- The Blazor portal calls the API through a typed client over `BrowserApiClient` (no hand-written anonymous response shapes in components); DTOs mirror the application contracts.
- MediatR is pinned to the last free/MIT version (12.4.x); revisit only if a licensing or feature need forces it.

Decision discipline:

- Do not introduce a new technology, hosting model, persistence strategy, API convention, authorization model, or module dependency pattern without updating the architecture document.
- When changing a decision, record the date, decision, and reason in the decisions log.
- Keep future flexibility in mind, but do not add infrastructure before there is a real business or measured operational need.
